packageMeta.name: purescript-sequences
packageMeta.description: An efficient, general purpose sequence type.

declarations.comments:
A Digit is just an array which has between one and four elements
(inclusive). If a Digit has two or three elements, it is described as
'safe'; otherwise, it is described as 'dangerous'.
declarations.title: Digit

declarations.comments:
Append a single element. This is partial because the result is not defined
in the case where the argument has 4 elements.
declarations.title: snocDigit

declarations.comments: Like mkDigit, except this returns Nothing on invalid input.
declarations.title: mkDigitMay

declarations.comments:
This function is only defined when the argument has between one and four
elements inclusive. It will not throw an error if this is not satisfied,
although the Digit length invariant will be violated, which will cause
other functions to break.
declarations.title: mkDigit

declarations.comments:
Prepend a single element. This is partial because the result is not defined
in the case where the argument has 4 elements.
declarations.title: consDigit

modules.name: Data.FingerTree
modules.comments:
This module defines a general-purpose data structure, known as a "finger
tree", which is intended to be used as a building block for implementing
other data structures. See, for example, `Seq` from `Data.Sequence`.

declarations.comments: This function throws an error if the argument is empty.
declarations.title: splitTree

declarations.comments:
Split a finger tree according to which elements satisfy a predicate. This
function is partial because it requires that the result of applying the
predicate to mempty is false; if this is not the case, the behaviour is
undefined.
declarations.title: split

declarations.comments:
A Digit is just an array which has between one and four elements
(inclusive). If a Digit has two or three elements, it is described as
'safe'; otherwise, it is described as 'dangerous'.
declarations.title: Digit

declarations.comments:
This function is only defined when the argument has between one and four
elements inclusive. It will not throw an error if this is not satisfied,
although the Digit length invariant will be violated, which will cause
other functions to break.
declarations.title: mkDigit

declarations.comments: Like mkDigit, except this returns Nothing on invalid input.
declarations.title: mkDigitMay

declarations.comments:
Append a single element. This is partial because the result is not defined
in the case where the argument has 4 elements.
declarations.title: snocDigit

declarations.comments:
Prepend a single element. This is partial because the result is not defined

declarations.title: consDigit

modules.name: Data.Sequence
modules.comments:
This module provides a sequence data type, intended for the same sort of
tasks as an Array would be in JavaScript, except with better asymptotic
complexity for many operations.

The implementation uses 2-3 finger trees annotated with sizes, as
described in the paper [_Finger Trees: A Simple General-Purpose Data
Structure_][1], Ralf Hinze and Ross Paterson, Journal of Functional
Programming 16:2 (2006) pp 197-217.

This module is intended to be imported qualified, to avoid name clashes.
For example:

```purescript
import Data.Sequence (Seq)
import Data.Sequence as Seq
```

[1]: http://staff.city.ac.uk/~ross/papers/FingerTree.pdf

declarations.comments: A sequence with no elements.
declarations.title: empty

declarations.comments: O(1). Create a Seq with one element.
declarations.title: singleton

declarations.comments: O(1). Add an element to the left end of a Seq.
declarations.title: cons

declarations.comments: O(1). Add an element to the right end of a Seq.
declarations.title: snoc

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(n1,n2)), where n1 and n2 are the lengths of the arguments. Join
two Seqs together.
declarations.title: append

declarations.comments:
O(m*log(n)), where m is the number of sequences, and n is the length of
the longest sequence within it. Flatten a sequence of sequences.
declarations.title: concat

declarations.comments:
O(m*n), where m is the number of sequences, and n is the length of the
longest sequence within it. Map a function over a sequence and then
flatten the results.
declarations.title: concatMap

declarations.comments: O(1). The number of elements in the sequence.
declarations.title: length

declarations.comments: O(1). True if the sequence has no elements, false otherwise.
declarations.title: null
uncons
unsnoc

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Split the sequence into two subsequences. The first
subsequence will have i elements (unless there are not that many in the
whole sequence, in which case the first element is the same sequence,
unchanged).
declarations.title: splitAt

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Take a certain number of values from the left end of
a sequence, and discard the rest.
declarations.title: take

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Discard a given number of elements from the left side
of a Seq.
declarations.title: drop

declarations.comments:
O(1). True if the given index specifies an element that exists in the
sequence, false otherwise.
declarations.title: inBounds

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Retrieve the element at the given index in the
sequence. This function is zero-based; that is, the first element in a
sequence `xs` can be retrieved with `index 0 xs`.
declarations.title: index

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Adjust the element at the specified index by
applying the given function to it. If the index is out of range, the
sequence is returned unchanged.
declarations.title: adjust

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Replace the element at the specified index with
a new element. If the index is out of range, the sequence is returned
unchanged.
declarations.title: replace

declarations.comments:
O(n). Apply a function to every element within a sequence. Note that this
function is performed lazily — the actual call is almost
instantaneous, regardless of the length of the sequence, because the
function is not applied to all elements immediately. The eventual running
time (assuming all elements are later requested) _is_ O(n), though.
declarations.title: map

declarations.comments: O(1). Get the first element of a Seq. Equivalent to `index 0`.
declarations.title: head

declarations.comments: O(1). Get all but the first element of a Seq. Equivalent to `drop 1`.
declarations.title: tail

declarations.comments:
O(1). Get all but the last element of a Seq. Equivalent to `\seq -> take
(length seq - 1)`.
declarations.title: init

declarations.comments:
O(1). Get the last element of a Seq. Equivalent to
`\seq -> index (length seq - 1) seq`.
declarations.title: last

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n*log(n)), but depends on the Foldable instance. Turn any
`Foldable` into a `Seq`.
declarations.title: fromFoldable

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n), but depends on the Unfoldable instance. Turn a `Seq` into
any `Unfoldable`.
declarations.title: toUnfoldable

declarations.comments:
O(n). Create a new Seq which contains only those elements of the input
Seq which satisfy the given predicate.
declarations.title: filter

declarations.comments:
O(n*log(n)). Sort the sequence, using the `sort` from
`Data.Sequence.Ordered`. Note that this sorting algorithm is unstable.
declarations.title: sort

declarations.comments: Force evaluation of all unevaluated thunks within the sequence.
declarations.title: fullyForce

modules.name: Data.Sequence.NonEmpty
modules.comments:
This module contains a type, `Seq`, much like that from `Data.Sequence`,
but which is guaranteed to contain at least one element.

This module is intended to be imported qualified, to avoid name clashes or
ambiguity. For example:

```purescript
import Data.Sequence.NonEmpty as NonEmpty
```

declarations.comments: A sequence which is guaranteed to contain at least one element.
declarations.title: Seq

declarations.comments: O(1). Construct a sequence from a single element.
declarations.title: singleton

declarations.comments: O(1). Add an element to the left end of a sequence.
declarations.title: cons

declarations.comments: O(1). Add an element to the right end of a sequence.
declarations.title: snoc

declarations.comments: O(log(min(i,n-i))). Join two sequence values together.
declarations.title: append

declarations.comments: O(1). The number of elements in the sequence.
declarations.title: length

declarations.comments:
O(1). True if the given index specifies an element that exists in the
sequence, false otherwise.
declarations.title: inBounds

declarations.comments:
O(1). Take one element off the left side of a Seq and return it, together
with the (possibly empty) remainder of the Seq.
declarations.title: uncons

declarations.comments:
O(1). Take one element off the right side of a Seq and return it, together
with the (possibly empty) remainder of the Seq.
declarations.title: unsnoc

declarations.comments:
O(1). Get the first element of a non-empty sequence. Equivalent to
`index 0`.
declarations.title: head

declarations.comments:
O(1). Get all but the first element of a non-empty sequence. The returned
sequence is possibly empty. Equivalent to `drop 1`.
declarations.title: tail

declarations.comments: O(1). Get all but the last element of a non-empty sequence. Possibly empty.
declarations.title: init

declarations.comments: O(1). Get the last element of a non-empty sequence.
declarations.title: last

declarations.comments:
O(1). Turn a non-empty sequence into a "plain" sequence (i.e. one from
Data.Sequence), containing the same elements.
declarations.title: toPlain

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Split the sequence into two (possibly empty) subsequences.
The first subsequence will have i elements (unless there are not that many in
the whole sequence, in which case the first element is the same sequence,
unchanged).
declarations.title: splitAt

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Take a certain number of values from the left end of
a sequence, and discard the rest, returning a possibly empty sequence.
declarations.title: take

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Discard a given number of elements from the left end
of a sequence, returning a possibly empty sequence.
declarations.title: drop

declarations.comments:
O(n). Create a new (possibly empty) sequence which contains only those
elements of the input sequence which satisfy the given predicate.
declarations.title: filter

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Retrieve the element at the given index in the
sequence. This function is zero-based; that is, the first element in a
sequence `xs` can be retrieved with `index 0 xs`.
declarations.title: index

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Adjust the element at the specified index by
applying the given function to it. If the index is out of range, the
sequence is returned unchanged.
declarations.title: adjust

declarations.comments:
O(log(min(i,n-i))). Replace the element at the specified index with
a new element. If the index is out of range, the sequence is returned
unchanged.
declarations.title: replace

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n), but depends on the Unfoldable instance. Turn a `Seq` into
any `Unfoldable`.
declarations.title: toUnfoldable

modules.name: Data.Sequence.Ordered
modules.comments:
This module defines a sequence where elements are always kept in
order. This enables constant time access to the least and greatest
elements, in addition to logarithmic time partitioning.

The module is intended to be imported qualified, to avoid ambiguity or
name clashes. For example:

```purescript
import Data.Sequence.Ordered (OrdSeq)
import Data.Sequence.Ordered as OrdSeq
```

declarations.comments: An ordered sequence. The Semigroup instance uses the `merge` function.
declarations.title: OrdSeq

declarations.comments: O(1). Returns true if the given sequence is empty, false otherwise.
declarations.title: null

declarations.comments: O(n). Return the length of the sequence.
declarations.title: length

declarations.comments:
O(log(n)). Split an ordered sequence into two halves. The first element
of the returned tuple contains all elements which compared less than or
equal to the argument; the second element contains the rest.
declarations.title: partition

declarations.comments: O(log(n)). Insert the given value into the correct place in the sequence.
declarations.title: insert

declarations.comments:
O(log(n)). Delete all elements from the sequence which compare EQ to the
given value.
declarations.title: deleteAll

declarations.comments:
O(m*log(n/m)), where m and n are the lengths of the longer and shorter
sequences respectively. Create a new sequence containing every element
in both of the given sequences.
declarations.title: merge

declarations.comments:
O(n*log(n)), where n is the length of the longer sequence. Create a new
sequence containing only elements which are common to both sequences.
declarations.title: intersection

declarations.comments:
O(1). Access the least element of the sequence, or Nothing if the sequence
is empty.
declarations.title: least

declarations.comments:
O(1). Remove the least element of the sequence, returning that element and
the remainder of the sequence. If the sequence is empty, return Nothing.
declarations.title: popLeast

declarations.comments:
O(1). Access the greatest element of the sequence, or Nothing if the
sequence is empty.
declarations.title: greatest

declarations.comments:
O(1). Remove the greatest element of the sequence, returning that element
and the remainder of the sequence. If the sequence is empty, return
Nothing.
declarations.title: popGreatest

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n*log(n)), but depends on the Foldable instance. Consruct an
ordered sequence from any any `Foldable`.
declarations.title: fromFoldable

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n), but depends on the Unfoldable instance. Unfold an ordered
sequence in ascending order.
declarations.title: toUnfoldable

declarations.comments:
Probably O(n), but depends on the Unfoldable instance. Unfold an ordered
sequence in descending order.
declarations.title: toUnfoldableDescending

declarations.comments:
Sort any structure (which has Foldable, Unfoldable, and Functor instances)
by converting to an OrdSeq and back again. I am fairly sure this is
usually O(n*log(n)), although of course this depends on the Unfoldable and
Foldable instances.
declarations.title: sort
